{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01AN9xcyst8Vsqv73PFhRh6p","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The transform is still at checkpoint 1 with `operations_behind: 2`. The `trigger_count` went from 3 to 11 (it's being triggered) and `last_search_time` updated. But the checkpoint is not advancing.\n\nThe transform is in `started` state but checkpoint isn't advancing past 1. This means:\n1. The transform is triggering searches (trigger_count went up)\n2. But not processing the new documents\n\nLooking at the `checkpointing`:\n- `last.timestamp_millis`: 1783108807585 (when checkpoint 1 completed)\n- `time_upper_bound_millis`: 1783108806585 (the sync delay boundary)\n- `changes_last_detected_at`: 1783108807563\n- `last_search_time`: 1783109407912 (updated recently)\n\nThe `time_upper_bound_millis` represents the cutoff for which documents should be included in the next checkpoint. Since the new documents have timestamps from 2026-01-02 and there's a 1-second sync delay, they should already be picked up. But it seems the sync delay calculation might be preventing them from being included.\n\nI'm realizing the issue might be with how the continuous transform handles checkpoints. The first checkpoint processes all existing data, then subsequent checkpoints should pick up new documents with timestamps newer than the previous checkpoint's `time_upper_bound_millis`. But if the checkpoint isn't advancing, it could mean the transform isn't detecting any documents that meet the time window criteria for the next checkpoint. So the new documents with January 2026 timestamps fall within the already-processed window from checkpoint 1 (which has an upper bound in July 2026), meaning the transform won't detect them as changes since it only looks forward in time—this is why they're not being picked up. Actually, I need to reconsider how ES transform sync works—it's not using a time-based watermark like I was think